Question: I'd like to telework from a country outside the EU for a couple of
  weeks. What is the annual cap on this, and within that period, what
  is the maximum I can do consecutively?
Example answer: Out of the maximum 90 working days per calendar year of teleworking
  from a location within the Union, members of staff may telework from
  a location outside the Union for up to 20 working days per calendar
  year. In addition, teleworking shall not exceed a maximum of 10
  consecutive working days, a limit that applies both within and
  across calendar months and also where teleworking is combined with
  leave, since leave does not interrupt the consecutiveness. (ECB
  Staff Rules, pages 83–84)
Predicted answer: 1. Annual cap: Members of staff may telework from a location outside
  the Union for up to 20 working days per calendar year (teleworking
  days are pro‑rated if joining, resuming, leaving or suspending work
  during the year). (ECB Staff Rules, 5.1bis.4, p.84)  2. Maximum
  consecutiveness (and monthly limit): Teleworking from a location
  within or outside the Union shall not exceed 10 consecutive working
  days, and members may telework for a maximum of 10 working days per
  calendar month. The consecutiveness limit applies within and across
  calendar months and is not interrupted by leave. (ECB Staff Rules,
  5.1bis.9, p.87; 5.1bis.4, p.84)  3. Operational points: A “working
  day” is eight hours for full‑time staff (or the proportional part
  for part‑time staff). Members must request authorisation and confirm
  they meet the IT, confidentiality and safety requirements;
  teleworking from outside the Union may only take place from
  countries compatible with ECB IT/confidentiality requirements. (ECB
  Staff Rules, 5.1bis.4, pp.83–84)  (ECB Staff Rules, 5.1bis.4,
  pp.83–84; 5.1bis.9, p.87)
