Question: I'm in salary band C and my line manager asked me to work several
  hours last Saturday because of a publication deadline. If I take
  payment instead of compensatory leave, how is the amount calculated?
Example answer: For members of staff with a basic salary up to step 59 of salary band
  E, overtime worked on Saturdays, Sundays and public holidays is
  compensated at two hours for each hour of overtime worked. Where
  compensatory leave for overtime cannot be granted, the member of
  staff may instead be granted overtime payment in lieu of leave, and
  the standard hourly rate for such payment is 0.6% of the basic
  monthly salary for the month in which the overtime was worked. (ECB
  Conditions of Employment, page 13; ECB Staff Rules, pages 89–90)
Predicted answer: 1. Main rule: If compensatory leave cannot be granted, overtime may be
  paid in lieu. The payment is calculated at a standard hourly rate
  equal to 0.6% of the basic monthly salary for the month in which the
  overtime was worked (ECB Staff Rules, §5.3.4–5.3.5, p.90).    2.
  Procedure and timing: Details of the overtime must be communicated
  to the Directorate General Human Resources by the third working day
  of the month following the month in which the overtime occurred,
  using the provided forms; the overtime payment is made with the
  monthly salary (ECB Staff Rules, §5.3.6, p.90).    3. Tax treatment:
  The overtime payment is subject to taxation at the rate which, in
  the month during which the overtime occurred, applied to the highest
  taxable amount of the member of staff’s salary (ECB Staff Rules,
  §5.3.7, p.90).    4. Note on alternatives: Members of staff up to
  step 59 of salary band E (which includes salary band C) are
  otherwise entitled to time-compensation rates set out in the
  Conditions of Employment, but the monetary rate when payment is
  chosen is as stated above (ECB Conditions of Employment, p.13; ECB
  Staff Rules, §5.3.5, p.90). (ECB Staff Rules, §§5.3.4–5.3.7, p.90;
  ECB Conditions of Employment, p.13)
