Question: My spouse, who was an ECB staff member, recently passed away while in
  service. What benefits apply with regard to salary continuation and
  to our return to our country of origin?
Example answer: In the event of the death of a staff member, payment of their salary
  and allowances is extended for three months. Where termination of
  service is caused by death, the resettlement benefits — coverage of
  travel-related expenses and removal of personal belongings, together
  with a resettlement allowance equal to 200% of the monthly basic
  salary for staff entitled to a household allowance or 100% otherwise
  — are paid, under the conditions laid down in the Staff Rules, to
  the surviving spouse or recognised partner or, in their absence, to
  the deceased staff member's dependent children. (ECB Conditions of
  Employment, pages 12, 19)
Predicted answer: 1. Salary continuation: Payment of the deceased member of staff’s
  salary and allowances is extended for three months following death
  (ECB Conditions of Employment, p.19, Art. 37).  2. Return to country
  of origin / repatriation:    2.1. The ECB shall reimburse the costs
  of repatriating the body from the member of staff’s place of
  employment to their original place of residence.      2.2. If the
  death occurs during official business travel, the ECB shall bear the
  costs of repatriation from the place where death occurs to the
  member of staff’s original place of residence or to their place of
  employment (ECB Staff Rules, p.116).  3. Related survivor relocation
  and removal benefits (where applicable): Persons entitled under the
  deceased member (e.g., surviving spouse/recognised partner or
  dependants) who resettle more than 50 kilometres from the ECB are
  entitled to benefits on termination that include reimbursement of
  travel and removal expenses; for resettlement outside the EU
  reimbursement is limited to the capital of the EU Member State
  furthest from the ECB or actual costs, whichever is lesser. Members
  (or persons entitled) recruited outside the EU may request
  relocation to the place of recruitment. Reimbursement of removal
  expenses may be paid to legal heirs if there is no surviving
  spouse/partner/children (ECB Staff Rules, Art. 4.2.2, p.72; ECB
  Staff Rules, p.70).  4. Additional financial entitlement (not
  strictly salary continuation but relevant for survivors): An
  indemnity equal to five times the deceased member’s annual basic
  salary is payable in the event of death, to the persons designated
  or entitled under the rules (ECB Conditions of Employment, p.16).
  (ECB Conditions of Employment, p.19, Art. 37; ECB Staff Rules,
  p.116; ECB Staff Rules, Art. 4.2.2, p.72; ECB Staff Rules, p.70; ECB
  Conditions of Employment, p.16.)
